  note = {\textbf{Extracted Annotations }
\par
{$>$}\emph{"Farming systems in West Africa have evolved over the last decades along a certain development pathway (e.g., Stoop et al., 1999). We will describe this development, in particular in relation to changes in indicators of management performance related to soil fertility maintenance at the farm level. At the time that the herdsman was pleading for a cure against land hunger, arable farming systems were at the point of change from fallow systems to permanent cropping. Earlier, these farming systems practised long fallow periods to sustain soil fertility and co-existed with pastoral systems, the latter supplying manure for the farmers fields in exchange for water, cereals, etc. (manure contracting). Schematically, farming systems dynamics can be described as follows (cf. Kant, 2001)." }

{$>$}\emph{"Increasing population pressure forced arable farmers to increase cereal production to maintain food self-sufficiency for their families. Introduction of animal traction supported attainment of this goal by allowing cultivation of more land and maintaining labour productivity. Increasingly thus, arable farmers became livestock owners themselves, their livestock grazing the crop residues and the contracting communal village pastures, leaving pastoralists with less and less land for grazing. Consequently, pastoral systems were at that point doomed to extinction." }

{$>$}\emph{"With continued increase in population pressure, soil fertility management in farming N. de Ridder et al.= Agricultural Systems 80 (2004) 109-131 117" }

{$>$}\emph{"systems is characterised by intensified internal recycling of nutrients. Crop residues are increasingly collected and transported to the homesteads to feed animals that are kept in kraals and stables. This practice creates the opportunity to collect the manure that, mixed with animal feed refusals and household waste, is applied to arable fields close to the homesteads. Farmers owning less or no livestock, use the technique of composting crop residues and household waste, returning the upgraded organic material to the fields" }

{$>$}\emph{"Ultimately, a farming system evolves with zero grazing, where roughage is collected from wastelands and road sides to be used as mulch on the fields, for composting or as feed for the animals. This intensification of internal recycling of nutrients is associated with an increase in labour productivity, indicating that innovations are selected that increase production per hectare through increased input of labour (Kuyvenhoven and Ruben, 2002). However, with continued increase in labour availability as a result of increasing population, labour migration and offfarm income become more and more important." }

{$>$}\emph{"Further increases in labour input ultimately do not result in further increases in production per hectare and thus lead to reduced labour productivity. When a critical lower threshold in labour productivity is reached, farmers can switch to soil fertility management based on external inputs, i.e. inorganic fertilisers." }

{$>$}\emph{"Farmers may also seek for off-farm employment, but then earnings are not necessarily reinvested in soil fertility (c.f. De Jager et al., 1998). Not investing in external inputs to maintain and improve soil fertility will finally leave no other option for farmers than to quit farming." }

{$>$}\emph{"If farmers aims and aspirations are to continue farming with increased use of external inputs, labour productivity increases again. However, this change in farming systems will only occur, if markets for inputs and produce of food and cash crops are available and if the farm (economic, political, social and bio-physical) environment is conducive." }

{$>$}\emph{"Recent data on the use of inorganic fertiliser in eight villages in W. Africa (Table 1) suggest introduction of inorganic fertiliser in farming systems at population pressures exceeding 40-60 inhabitants per km2." }},
  file = {/home/enzo/WORK_PHD/Obsidian_vaults/My_references/de Ridder_et_al/2004/de_Ridder_et_al2004_Revisiting_a_‘cure_against_land_hunger’.pdf}
